==English==
===Etymology===
Latin [[periplus#Latin|periplus]], from Greek [[περιπλους]], from [[περι-]] + [[πλους]] ‘journey’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'pɛrɪplʌs/

===Noun===
{{en-noun2|'''periplus'''|'''[[peripli]]''' or '''[[periploi]]'''}}
# a [[circumnavigation]]; a sea [[voyage]] around a coastline
# a record of such a voyage
#:*'''1974''': the map of the world Ptolemy followed in his geography, finding the longitude that passed through the Gates of Herakles and the island of Rhodes, and placing north and south of it the world as recorded on the '''periploi''' of the Phoenician merchants — Guy Davenport, ''Tatlin!''